# Vue Architecture

## Default stack

- Vue 3 + Composition API + `<script setup lang="ts">` (always include `lang="ts"`)
- Prefer Composition API unless the project explicitly requires Options API
- Prefer templates over JSX unless the project already uses JSX
- In this Nuxt app, keep `app.vue` / `pages/*` as thin composition surfaces

## Core principles

- One source of truth; derive everything else
- Props down, events up
- Small, focused components
- Prefer `computed` over template logic or unnecessary watchers

## Before coding (non-trivial features)

Sketch a short component map:

- One sentence responsibility per component
- Keep route/page/app shells as composition surfaces only
- Move feature UI and logic into feature components/composables
- Define typed props/emits for each child
- Prefer `components/<feature>/...` and `composables/use<Feature>.ts` when adding 2+ components

## Split triggers

Split if any are true:

- Orchestration/state plus substantial multi-section UI
- 3+ distinct UI sections (form, filters, list, footer)
- Repeated template blocks (rows, cards, list items)

For CRUD/list features, split at least into: container, form/input, list/item, footer/filters.

Allow a single-file approach only for tiny demos; justify why splitting is unnecessary.
